    steps: [
      { stepNumber: 1, title: 'Make and boil the gatte', instruction: 'Mix besan with 60g curd, 5g mustard oil, 1g cumin seeds, fennel seeds, 1g turmeric, 2g red chilli powder, and salt. Knead into a stiff, non-sticky dough — stiffer than roti dough. Divide into 3 portions. Roll each into a 1.5cm diameter rope. Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Drop the ropes in and boil 8-10 minutes until they float and feel firm when pressed. Remove, cool slightly, cut into 3cm pieces (the gatte).', durationMins: 15, technique: 'boil', kitchenNote: 'Gatte must be stiff dough — soft dough produces gatte that disintegrate in the gravy. The stiff texture also means they hold shape during boiling and gravy cooking.' },
      { stepNumber: 2, title: 'Build the yoghurt gravy', instruction: 'Heat mustard oil to smoking in a kadai, remove 30 seconds, return to medium heat. Add cumin seeds and hing — sizzle 20 seconds. Add chopped onion and cook 5 minutes until golden. Add garlic and ginger, cook 2 minutes. Add tomato and cook 4 minutes until soft. Reduce heat to low. Whisk remaining curd smooth and add slowly while stirring continuously — do not add cold curd over high heat or it will split. Add remaining turmeric, red chilli powder, coriander powder, and salt.', durationMins: 14, technique: 'saute', kitchenNote: 'The critical technique here is adding curd over LOW heat while stirring constantly. Curd added to a hot pan over high heat splits immediately — grainy, curdled gravy cannot be recovered.' },
      { stepNumber: 3, title: 'Combine and simmer', instruction: 'Add boiled gatte to the yoghurt gravy. Stir gently. Simmer on low heat 8 minutes — the gatte will absorb the gravy and swell slightly. The gravy should cling to each piece and look smooth and golden-orange. Add garam masala, crushed kasuri methi, and lemon juice. Garnish with fresh coriander.', durationMins: 10, technique: 'simmer', kitchenNote: 'Gatte ki sabzi improves after 30 min rest — the gatte fully absorb the gravy flavours. Excellent for batch cooking.' },
      { stepNumber: 4, title: 'Make bajra roti and pack', instruction: 'Knead bajra flour with hot water into a soft dough. Pat two thick 5-inch circles. Cook on tawa 3 min each side — bajra takes longer than wheat. Pack gatte in main compartment. Bajra rotis wrapped in foil.', durationMins: 8, technique: 'assemble', kitchenNote: 'Bajra roti hardens within 20 min of cooking. Wrap immediately in foil. Pack hot.' },
    ],
